#week-title("Two", "The Court Cards & Alchemical Temperaments")

=== Core Teaching

The four court cards (Page, Knight, Queen, King) in each suit map onto the
four Paracelsian temperaments and also onto four stages of the alchemical
practitioner's development through any domain of the Work.

*The Paracelsian Temperaments* are not personality types in the modern
psychological sense — they are elemental constitutions, describing the balance
of the four elements as it expresses in a person's manner of engaging with the
world:

- *Choleric (Fire):* Hot and dry. Fast, decisive, easily roused, prone to
  anger, creative under pressure. In the laboratory: tends to move quickly,
  may rush operations.
- *Phlegmatic (Water):* Cold and wet. Patient, receptive, emotionally sensitive,
  reflective, prone to inertia. In the laboratory: excellent at observation and
  long digestions; may avoid decisions.
- *Sanguine (Air):* Hot and wet. Social, optimistic, idea-generating, easily
  distracted, versatile. In the laboratory: excellent at making connections and
  reading correspondence tables; may lack follow-through.
- *Melancholic (Earth):* Cold and dry. Methodical, detail-oriented, prone to
  depression and perfectionism, thorough. In the laboratory: excellent record-
  keeper; may over-refine and over-calcine.

The court cards applied to the practitioner's stage of development:

- *Page:* The Tyro — approaching the mystery with fresh eyes, eager but
  unformed. Stage of enthusiasm and foundational learning.
- *Knight:* The active practitioner — in the midst of the Work, moving with
  energy and commitment, not yet mastery. Stage of effort and refinement.
- *Queen:* Mastery of the inner dimension of the element — receptive,
  integrated, able to sense rather than merely measure. Stage of developed
  intuition.
- *King:* The Adept in full command — authoritative, settled, having completed
  the Work in that elemental domain. Stage of stable expression.

A student who is a Page of Fire in the laboratory (enthusiastic, impatient,
burning through preparations) may simultaneously be a Queen of Water in their
inner work (deeply receptive, sensitive to the subtle signs of the Desoille
movements). The court cards allow a nuanced self-reading of where the Work
stands across multiple dimensions.

=== Topics This Week

- The four Paracelsian temperaments: Choleric, Phlegmatic, Sanguine, Melancholic
- Identifying your own temperamental constitution through the court cards
- Page, Knight, Queen, King as stages of development in each elemental domain
- Reading your laboratory and inner work constitution against the court framework
- Recognizing constitutional imbalances that affect the Work

#inner-work[
  *The Constitutional Reading*

  Separate the sixteen court cards from the deck. Lay them in a four-by-four
  grid (four suits by four ranks).

  Without deliberate choice, select one card from each row (one Page, one
  Knight, one Queen, one King) that feels most resonant with your current
  stage in each domain.

  Record the four cards and write a paragraph on what the combination reveals
  about your alchemical constitution. Where are you most developed? Where
  are you still at the Page stage?
]

